column24:
Healey Cars

Direct descendants of the great Donald Healey, inventor of the famous 'Austin Healey' car - we have an innate passion for cars. Over the years, we have built a small and treasured collection of Healeys Cars - some of which we have on display

We have a range of Healey Cars on display.  They are all road worthy – and when the sun is shining you may well find a few less on display than if its raining :)  They are all driven by the Healeys on regular occurrences… but a little overview of the cars we have is below

Healey Silverstone

The Healey Silverstone is an open two-seater road / racing sports car, or in the USA roadster, that was made by Donald Healey Motor Company. The Silverstone had headlights behind the grille to make it more aerodynamic. It was designed to be a dual purpose “race and ride” car. It also had a 104 horsepower 2.5L Riley I-4 engine and four speed manual transmission.

Austin Healey 3000

The Austin-Healey 3000 is a British sports car built from 1959 to 1967, and is the best known of the “big Healey” models. The car’s bodywork was made by Jensen Motors, and the vehicles were assembled by Austin-Healey at the Abingdon works.

The 3-litre 3000 was a highly successful car, which won its class in many European rallies in its heyday and is still raced in classic car competitions by enthusiasts today.

Austin Healey Sprite

The Austin-Healey Sprite is a small open sports car that was announced to the press in Monte Carlo by BMC on 20 May 1958, just before that year’s Monaco Grand Prix. It was intended to be a low-cost model that “a chap could keep in his bike shed”, yet be the successor to the sporting versions of the pre-war Austin Seven. The Sprite was designed by the Donald Healey Motor Company, with production being undertaken by Austin-Healey. It first went on sale at a price of £669, using a tuned version of the Austin A-Series engine and as many other components from existing cars as possible to keep costs down.

column24: Ok, so bear with me in the telling. I'm at a loss. ..Recently I've been keeping an eye out for interesting things to take pictures of with my macro lens. Spring is a great time for that because all plants start tiny (Last spring I went on a macro shooting spree and got some of my best work)...You see before you the roots of a Christmas Cactus. This particular cactus started out small. It was 3-segments of a larger plant my mom harvested for me 3 or 4 years ago from my grandmother's house. My grandmother's plant has been in her care for over 50 years...At no point in my lifetime have my grandmother and music ever been separated. For years she taught piano lessons in her house. She was closely involved in the musical education of my three sisters and I. She majored in trumpet at the University of Michigan way back when and played the organ in church for years and years...Isn't it both fantastic and unreal that a cutting from the cactus plant which absorbed thousands of hours worth of piano vibrations would develop roots that look surprisingly like a treble clef? Plants don't have feelings much less a way to discern a symbol denoting the range at and above 261.6 hertz (middle C)... but maybe this is just something else entirely...Coincidence?...
